1
00:00:59,210 --> 00:01:03,010
Chris, what is it?

2
00:01:04,410 --> 00:01:08,210
I love you so much.

3
00:01:09,710 --> 00:01:12,810
Don't you love me any more?

4
00:01:25,210 --> 00:01:29,110
I've made progress,
and I recognise that.

5
00:01:29,610 --> 00:01:35,210
But my wife, who I can't
even convince to come here...

6
00:01:35,610 --> 00:01:39,210
Anything can set her off.
It could be the phone ringing,

7
00:01:39,610 --> 00:01:43,610
something on the news,
something online, going shopping maybe.

8
00:01:44,010 --> 00:01:48,510
A commemorative T-shirt in the window.
It just puts her right back in that place,

9
00:01:48,910 --> 00:01:53,810
and it's like all my progress - ripped away.
And I'm right back there with her.

10
00:01:54,310 --> 00:01:59,410
I feel totally the opposite. I see the TV
and I see the Internet and I see those T-shirts

11
00:01:59,810 --> 00:02:05,810
and I feel nothing. The more I see the images,
the less I feel, the less I believe that it's real.

12
00:02:06,310 --> 00:02:12,310
I mean, I think I'm supposed to feel
something by now. Don't you think so?

13
00:02:14,510 --> 00:02:18,010
Linda, this is Chris Kelvin.
I'm returning your call.

14
00:02:18,510 --> 00:02:21,410
I have two times available this week;

15
00:02:21,710 --> 00:02:26,510
7am on Tuesday
or 6.15pm on Thursday.

16
00:02:27,010 --> 00:02:33,510
You can leave a message if either
of those times are good for you. Thank you.

17
00:02:34,010 --> 00:02:36,610
Well, I know that's not true.

18
00:02:37,010 --> 00:02:41,710
Because I know you, and I know it's not true.

19
00:02:46,410 --> 00:02:48,910
Good. I'm glad.

20
00:02:49,310 --> 00:02:50,910
All right.

21
00:02:51,210 --> 00:02:55,110
Let's pick this up on Wednesday.

22
00:03:59,210 --> 00:04:01,610
Can I help you?

23
00:04:02,010 --> 00:04:06,210
<i>We're looking for Dr Chris Kelvin.</i>

24
00:04:10,610 --> 00:04:13,710
<i>Chris...</i>

25
00:04:15,110 --> 00:04:19,910
<i>I can't imagine what you must be
thinking, getting a message like this.</i>

26
00:04:20,310 --> 00:04:27,010
<i>I apologise if it seems melodramatic, but
you are the only person I can... I can trust...</i>

27
00:04:27,610 --> 00:04:30,810
<i>in the situation.</i>

28
00:04:31,210 --> 00:04:33,610
<i>I need your help.</i>

29
00:04:33,910 --> 00:04:36,410
<i>I need you to come to Solaris, Chris.</i>

30
00:04:36,910 --> 00:04:40,710
<i>I don't know how to describe
what we are experiencing up here.</i>

31
00:04:41,010 --> 00:04:46,210
<i>We can't even agree amongst ourselves
what is... what is happening, or...</i>

32
00:04:46,810 --> 00:04:50,510
<i>what to do about it.</i>

33
00:04:51,210 --> 00:04:57,210
<i>I suppose the... the most obvious
solution would be to leave.</i>

34
00:04:57,710 --> 00:05:04,410
<i>But none of us want to. That's why
you're getting this... this bizarre request.</i>

35
00:05:04,910 --> 00:05:07,710
<i>I...</i>

36
00:05:08,110 --> 00:05:11,910
<i>I told the crew that your
background and experiences</i>

37
00:05:12,310 --> 00:05:17,310
<i>made you the...
the ideal candidate for this job.</i>

38
00:05:17,810 --> 00:05:20,010
<i>Don't worry. I didn't elaborate.</i>

39
00:05:21,910 --> 00:05:24,610
<i>But it's true.</i>

40
00:05:25,010 --> 00:05:28,410
<i>So, anyway...</i>

41
00:05:30,010 --> 00:05:33,410
<i>I, uh... I hope you will come to Solaris, Chris.</i>

42
00:05:33,810 --> 00:05:36,410
<i>L- I think you need to.</i>

43
00:05:36,810 --> 00:05:39,910
<i>You will see what I mean.</i>

44
00:05:40,410 --> 00:05:46,510
<i>I wish I could be more specific
about all of this, but... you know.</i>

45
00:05:47,110 --> 00:05:50,910
<i>People are listening.</i>

46
00:05:54,610 --> 00:06:00,810
You can imagine the distress
Dr Gibarian's message caused at DBA.

47
00:06:03,210 --> 00:06:05,610
Why not send in the security force?

48
00:06:05,910 --> 00:06:10,310
We did. We lost contact
as they were approaching Solaris.

49
00:06:10,810 --> 00:06:14,310
They haven't returned.

50
00:06:14,710 --> 00:06:17,510
There must be some
sort of on-board Al system.

51
00:06:17,810 --> 00:06:19,610
They shut it down.

52
00:06:19,910 --> 00:06:24,110
The company was hoping to solve
this problem without involving a civilian.

53
00:06:24,510 --> 00:06:28,810
Obviously these are extreme circumstances.

54
00:06:29,310 --> 00:06:32,910
Some preparation is involved
but you shouldn't have any trouble.

55
00:06:33,210 --> 00:06:39,510
The flight itself is fully automated.
You'll be asleep most of the trip.

56
00:06:40,710 --> 00:06:47,710
We feel confident that if you board
the ship, you can negotiate their safe return.

57
00:06:48,210 --> 00:06:51,610
Is that what everybody wants?

58
00:06:52,010 --> 00:06:55,510
Of course.

59
00:12:21,510 --> 00:12:25,410
Find the probability of F.

60
00:12:28,010 --> 00:12:31,910
OK, stop. Go back.

61
00:12:33,810 --> 00:12:37,310
Snow.

62
00:12:56,010 --> 00:12:59,210
Kelvin, is it?

63
00:12:59,610 --> 00:13:01,210
Yeah.

64
00:13:01,610 --> 00:13:05,310
Kelvin. Right. Oh, man.

65
00:13:05,710 --> 00:13:08,010
Sorry about that, Kelvin.

66
00:13:08,410 --> 00:13:10,410
Names, you know, just...

67
00:13:10,710 --> 00:13:12,810
For some reason. It, uh...

68
00:13:13,210 --> 00:13:15,610
Yeah. Uh...

69
00:13:15,910 --> 00:13:18,910
Well, uh, you wanna come in?

70
00:13:19,310 --> 00:13:21,410
I'm fine.

71
00:13:21,710 --> 00:13:26,610
Whose blood is that, leading to the lab?

72
00:13:27,110 --> 00:13:30,610
Yeah. Blood.

73
00:13:30,710 --> 00:13:34,110
How 'bout that?

74
00:13:37,410 --> 00:13:39,410
Katarn.

75
00:13:39,710 --> 00:13:41,610
He, um... Yeah.

76
00:13:41,910 --> 00:13:46,810
Security forces showed up
and he just took off, and they...

77
00:13:47,310 --> 00:13:50,510
Yeah. Put a hole in his pot.

78
00:13:50,910 --> 00:13:54,610
What happened to Gibarian?

79
00:13:55,910 --> 00:13:57,810
Yeah.

80
00:13:58,110 --> 00:14:01,910
It was a suicide.

81
00:14:03,110 --> 00:14:04,810
Who found him?

82
00:14:05,210 --> 00:14:08,110
I found him.

83
00:14:08,510 --> 00:14:11,710
What happened to Rhys?

84
00:14:12,010 --> 00:14:14,510
Yeah, now, Rhys w... Huh.

85
00:14:14,810 --> 00:14:18,910
We don't know, because the thing is,
he kind of... disappeared.

86
00:14:19,310 --> 00:14:21,110
- Disappeared?
- Disappeared.

87
00:14:21,410 --> 00:14:25,910
- How did he disappear?
- Exactly.

88
00:14:26,610 --> 00:14:29,710
Don't know. We do know
that he's not on the ship, uh,

89
00:14:30,010 --> 00:14:34,210
and that's... that's all we know.

90
00:14:34,610 --> 00:14:37,010
Where's Dr Gordon?

91
00:14:37,310 --> 00:14:40,810
Dr Gordon. She is in her room,

92
00:14:41,210 --> 00:14:42,910
and, um...

93
00:14:43,310 --> 00:14:47,510
Dr Gordon won't let you in her room.

94
00:14:51,910 --> 00:14:56,410
Can you tell me what's happening here?

95
00:14:57,110 --> 00:14:59,410
I could tell you what's happening,

96
00:14:59,810 --> 00:15:02,510
but, uh...

97
00:15:02,810 --> 00:15:08,310
I don't know if that'd
really tell you what's happening.

98
00:15:14,510 --> 00:15:17,510
I just wanna talk to you.

99
00:15:17,910 --> 00:15:23,310
You have to give me your word
you won't try to come in.

100
00:15:26,510 --> 00:15:30,010
All right.

101
00:15:44,610 --> 00:15:46,310
Well?

102
00:15:46,710 --> 00:15:50,410
- What happened to Gibarian?
- Didn't you talk to Snow?

103
00:15:50,710 --> 00:15:54,010
- I wanted to hear your version.
- There isn't any version.

104
00:15:54,410 --> 00:15:58,210
He killed himself.

105
00:15:59,110 --> 00:16:04,210
Why haven't you come home?
What happened here?

106
00:16:04,610 --> 00:16:08,610
What did you find?

107
00:16:08,910 --> 00:16:12,810
- Who are you representing?
- I'm the last effort to recover this mission,

108
00:16:13,210 --> 00:16:17,910
before they abandon this ship
and everyone on board.

109
00:16:26,710 --> 00:16:31,010
Until it starts happening to you,
there's really no point in discussing it.

110
00:16:54,910 --> 00:16:58,210
Hey.

111
00:17:04,510 --> 00:17:07,810
Hey!

112
00:17:22,710 --> 00:17:26,210
<i>- Who else is here?
- Who else is here?</i>

113
00:17:26,710 --> 00:17:30,210
<i>I saw a boy.</i>

114
00:17:33,210 --> 00:17:37,110
Gibarian's son.

115
00:17:37,710 --> 00:17:42,010
- Michael.
- How is that possible?

116
00:17:42,510 --> 00:17:45,410
I think that's why you're here.

117
00:17:45,810 --> 00:17:49,410
I want a formal interview with you
and Gordon. I'll need your help with her.

118
00:17:49,810 --> 00:17:52,210
Yeah. All right.

119
00:17:52,510 --> 00:17:53,610
Um...

120
00:17:53,910 --> 00:17:56,110
How much sleep do you need, Kelvin?

121
00:17:56,510 --> 00:17:58,910
- How much sleep?
- Yeah.

122
00:17:59,210 --> 00:18:03,910
- How long can you go without sleep?
- Depends.

123
00:18:05,010 --> 00:18:06,210
Well,

124
00:18:06,610 --> 00:18:09,810
when you do go to sleep,

125
00:18:10,110 --> 00:18:15,110
I find I sleep much better
with the door locked.

126
00:18:17,810 --> 00:18:23,310
<i>I was with the project when it was
still with NASA, before it was sold to DBA.</i>

127
00:18:23,810 --> 00:18:25,710
I was trained in physics.

128
00:18:26,110 --> 00:18:30,510
I was sent here to assess
the economic potential of Solaris.

129
00:18:31,010 --> 00:18:36,610
Whether or not it was a viable commercial
property or possible energy source.

130
00:18:37,010 --> 00:18:41,110
I was still compiling data
when this shit started happening.

131
00:18:41,610 --> 00:18:44,210
Did you run any tests
on the food, air, water?

132
00:18:44,710 --> 00:18:51,310
I checked it 50 times. There are no signs of
contaminants or psychotropic compounds.

133
00:18:53,610 --> 00:18:57,710
How about you? How are you doing?

134
00:18:58,810 --> 00:19:00,510
Depression.

135
00:19:00,910 --> 00:19:05,510
Along with bouts of hypomania
and primary insomnia.

136
00:19:05,910 --> 00:19:09,610
Suggestions of agoraphobia,
obsessive-compulsive disorder,

137
00:19:10,010 --> 00:19:12,010
shock, fatigue, denial...

138
00:19:12,410 --> 00:19:16,110
- Not unusual, given the circumstances.
- I know.

139
00:19:16,510 --> 00:19:22,410
All right. Now, what can you tell me
about what's happening here?

140
00:19:22,910 --> 00:19:28,110
Just that I want it to stop,
but I want to stop it.

141
00:19:28,710 --> 00:19:34,010
If I can stop it that means
I'm smarter than it is.

142
00:19:39,210 --> 00:19:44,310
You know you can go home,
walk away from all of this.

143
00:19:44,710 --> 00:19:48,610
I can guarantee it.

144
00:19:54,210 --> 00:19:56,410
Yeah.

145
00:19:56,810 --> 00:20:02,510
The thing is... Man, I would kill
to go back there. I'd... kill.

146
00:20:03,010 --> 00:20:05,510
But Gordon?

147
00:20:05,810 --> 00:20:10,510
Gordon happens to be Gordon, you know?

148
00:20:10,910 --> 00:20:14,410
So, um...

149
00:20:18,310 --> 00:20:21,710
But I'll see what I can do.

150
00:20:22,110 --> 00:20:26,310
<i>We take off into the cosmos.</i>

151
00:20:26,910 --> 00:20:31,910
<i>Ready for anything -
solitude, hardship, exhaustion...</i>

152
00:20:32,410 --> 00:20:35,510
<i>death.</i>

153
00:20:36,810 --> 00:20:38,810
<i>We're proud of ourselves.</i>

154
00:20:39,110 --> 00:20:44,610
<i>But when you think about it,
our enthusiasm's a sham.</i>

155
00:20:47,710 --> 00:20:52,810
<i>We don't want other worlds. We want mirrors.</i>

156
00:23:40,910 --> 00:23:43,710
So, anyway... How's the spawn?

157
00:23:44,010 --> 00:23:47,410
Oh, good, good. He cries
and shits in his pants every two hours.

158
00:23:47,910 --> 00:23:51,410
I know the feeling.

159
00:23:51,710 --> 00:23:53,610
When are you leaving?

160
00:23:53,910 --> 00:23:57,410
- We've been postponed again.
- I didn't hear that.

161
00:23:57,910 --> 00:23:59,510
Nobody knows yet.

162
00:23:59,910 --> 00:24:04,110
The governments are looking for a buyer. I
wish we could tell people what's happening.

163
00:24:04,410 --> 00:24:06,510
You can tell me. I'm a doctor.

164
00:24:06,910 --> 00:24:10,710
Well, Doctor, as we study Solaris,

165
00:24:11,110 --> 00:24:15,110
the most interesting thing is it, um...

166
00:24:15,510 --> 00:24:20,010
Well, it seems to be reacting.
Almost like it knows it's being observed.

167
00:24:20,510 --> 00:24:23,010
We can't explain it.

168
00:24:23,410 --> 00:24:27,010
Are you listening to me? Chris?

169
00:24:28,610 --> 00:24:32,410
- So anyway...
- So anyway. Sorry.

170
00:24:32,910 --> 00:24:38,810
Go to her. Her name is Rheya. She's a bit
tricky but, um, I guess she's worthwhile.

171
00:24:39,410 --> 00:24:41,310
Maybe she needs a shrink.

172
00:24:41,710 --> 00:24:45,110
Don't we all?

173
00:25:30,010 --> 00:25:33,710
Don't blow it.

174
00:25:37,910 --> 00:25:39,410
<i>You start.</i>

175
00:25:39,710 --> 00:25:41,710
<i>I did.</i>

176
00:25:42,010 --> 00:25:43,610
<i>Really?</i>

177
00:25:43,910 --> 00:25:50,010
All right, I'm gonna resist the impulse
to ask you about the door knob.

178
00:25:50,410 --> 00:25:53,710
- Do you always resist your impulses?
- Not always.

179
00:25:55,710 --> 00:25:59,610
<i>Try poetry.</i>

180
00:26:00,210 --> 00:26:03,010
<i>"And death shall have no dominion."</i>

181
00:26:03,310 --> 00:26:06,910
<i>Mm. Thomas.</i>

182
00:26:07,410 --> 00:26:11,710
<i>It's not a very happy poem, though.</i>

183
00:26:11,910 --> 00:26:18,410
<i>Well, you didn't seem
very happy when I saw you on the train.</i>

184
00:26:21,910 --> 00:26:24,210
<i>I wasn't.</i>

185
00:26:24,610 --> 00:26:28,010
<i>And tonight?</i>

186
00:26:29,210 --> 00:26:32,910
<i>It's early.</i>

187
00:29:15,210 --> 00:29:18,610
Goddammit!

188
00:29:53,210 --> 00:29:55,610
I'm awake.

189
00:29:56,010 --> 00:29:59,210
Yes.

190
00:29:59,710 --> 00:30:01,810
How are you here?

191
00:30:02,110 --> 00:30:04,110
How are you here?

192
00:30:04,510 --> 00:30:07,810
How do you mean?

193
00:30:08,210 --> 00:30:14,710
Where do you think you are?
Where do you think you are right now?

194
00:30:15,410 --> 00:30:18,510
At home.

195
00:30:18,910 --> 00:30:22,810
Where is home?

196
00:30:23,210 --> 00:30:26,310
With you, where we live.

197
00:30:26,810 --> 00:30:33,710
And do you remember being anywhere else
with me? Being together anywhere else?

198
00:30:35,210 --> 00:30:39,710
- Our apartment.
- Describe it.

199
00:30:40,610 --> 00:30:44,910
It's dark. It's very very dark.

200
00:30:46,210 --> 00:30:50,310
And there are no paintings on the wall.

201
00:30:50,710 --> 00:30:54,010
No pictures anywhere.

202
00:30:54,310 --> 00:30:59,810
No pictures on the fridge, even,
which I always thought was a bit strange.

203
00:31:00,310 --> 00:31:05,510
Do you remember
where we first saw each other?

204
00:31:06,810 --> 00:31:10,510
On a train.

205
00:31:19,010 --> 00:31:22,110
Chris...

206
00:31:28,410 --> 00:31:32,410
I'm so happy to see you.

207
00:31:33,310 --> 00:31:37,210
I love you so much.

208
00:31:42,010 --> 00:31:46,310
Don't you love me any more?

209
00:31:49,810 --> 00:31:53,010
I have to check out something with the crew.

210
00:31:53,310 --> 00:31:54,910
No! No!

211
00:31:55,210 --> 00:32:00,210
- Don't leave me! Don't leave me!
- Why? Why?

212
00:32:01,510 --> 00:32:05,210
- Why?
- I don't know.

213
00:32:06,910 --> 00:32:10,410
I don't know.

214
00:32:12,710 --> 00:32:14,510
It's OK.

215
00:32:14,810 --> 00:32:18,310
It's OK.

216
00:32:27,010 --> 00:32:30,910
Why are you sitting over there?

217
00:32:34,510 --> 00:32:38,810
Can I come and sit with you?

218
00:33:57,710 --> 00:34:01,010
Hey.

219
00:34:04,110 --> 00:34:08,210
What was that?

220
00:34:10,110 --> 00:34:11,810
Yeah.

221
00:34:12,110 --> 00:34:15,310
How 'bout that?

222
00:34:15,810 --> 00:34:19,610
Still workin' on that.

223
00:34:22,610 --> 00:34:25,210
Where's your visitor?

224
00:34:25,710 --> 00:34:30,110
I don't know. Stopped appearing.

225
00:34:31,110 --> 00:34:35,310
- Who's your visitor?
- My brother.

226
00:34:54,310 --> 00:34:57,610
Who was it?

227
00:34:58,110 --> 00:35:01,610
My wife.

228
00:35:02,610 --> 00:35:05,710
Dead?

229
00:35:13,210 --> 00:35:17,110
So what was her name?

230
00:35:18,010 --> 00:35:21,910
Will she come back?

231
00:35:27,510 --> 00:35:31,110
Do you want her to?

232
00:36:29,210 --> 00:36:30,910
- No, it isn't.
- Yes, it is.

233
00:36:31,210 --> 00:36:34,210
- No, it isn't. It's crap.
- Only one way to find out.

234
00:36:34,510 --> 00:36:37,710
You can submit it to someone
and see if they publish it.

235
00:36:38,110 --> 00:36:40,310
That's not an indication of anything.

236
00:36:40,610 --> 00:36:45,210
So no one else's opinion counts
except for yours?

237
00:36:45,610 --> 00:36:48,810
- Yeah.
- That's insane.

238
00:36:49,210 --> 00:36:51,410
- "That's" insane.
- I like it.

239
00:36:51,710 --> 00:36:56,010
Brings out the red in my eyes.

240
00:36:58,710 --> 00:37:01,810
So, did you show it to your father?

241
00:37:02,210 --> 00:37:03,910
- Yeah.
- And?

242
00:37:04,210 --> 00:37:06,610
- And he liked it.
- What'd he say?

243
00:37:06,910 --> 00:37:10,910
- He said he liked it.
- Well...

244
00:37:11,510 --> 00:37:16,910
He's a man who doesn't pass out
compliments very easily. That's something.

245
00:37:17,310 --> 00:37:20,910
- What's that tell you?
- Can we talk about something else? Please?

246
00:37:21,310 --> 00:37:25,610
All right. When do you wanna get hitched?

247
00:37:28,210 --> 00:37:32,910
Every time I bring it up
you make a joke about it, and...

248
00:37:33,510 --> 00:37:37,610
I know, I know. That's pathet...
I'm sorry. It's just...

249
00:37:37,910 --> 00:37:39,810
It-it's so difficult for me.

